(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 2 :title "Chapter 2 — Sorting, visualized" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/02-sorting-viz.md" :size 12809 :sha256 "bf7c56e0acf7d9b1" :content "---\nslug: book-reference-ch-02\nbook: reference\nchapter: 2\ntitle: Sorting, visualized\npart: appendix\nof: reference-manual\napp: none\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane AJ)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\npalette:\n  background: canvas-cream\n  top-band: magic\n  center: canvas-mint\n  ink: warm-plum\n  pink: sakura-pink (Sakura only)\nprev: 01-conway\nnext: 03-tail-recursion\n---\n\n# Chapter 2 — Sorting, visualized\n\nSorting is the second classic. Every programmer writes bubble sort at some point; not everyone writes it in a way that shows the compares and swaps happening. This chapter does both: the sort algorithms themselves, and a small trace layer that turns each compare and swap into a printable line so you can watch the sort happen in the REPL.\n\nThree sorts: bubble (as slow as it looks), insertion (as tidy as it looks), quicksort (as recursive as Scheme wants). All three end up sorting the same list, but the trace shows why the three feel so different.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> When I first read the sorting algorithms as a person new to CS, they were opaque — you get told bubble is slow and quicksort is fast, and you sort of nod. When I could *watch* the compares scroll by, I finally believed it. The trace is what turned \"true\" into \"obvious.\"\n\n## The trace helper\n\nStart with the small piece that all three sorts share: a way to print what just happened.\n\n```scheme\n(define (trace label a b)\n  (display label) (display \": \")\n  (display a) (display \" vs \") (display b) (newline))\n\n(trace 'compare 3 5)\n(trace 'swap    5 3)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\ncompare: 3 vs 5\nswap: 5 vs 3\n```\n\nTwo lines. The trace layer is deliberately tiny — the point is to make the sort visible without cluttering the sort code.\n\n## Bubble sort\n\nBubble sort walks the list, compares adjacent pairs, swaps if out of order, repeats until a full pass makes no swaps. In Scheme, that is a two-level recursion.\n\n```scheme\n(define (trace label a b)\n  (display label) (display \": \")\n  (display a) (display \" vs \") (display b) (newline))\n\n(define (bubble-pass lst)\n  (cond\n    ((null? lst) '())\n    ((null? (cdr lst)) lst)\n    (else\n     (let ((a (car lst)) (b (cadr lst)) (rest (cddr lst)))\n       (trace 'compare a b)\n       (cond\n         ((> a b)\n          (trace 'swap a b)\n          (cons b (bubble-pass (cons a rest))))\n         (else\n          (cons a (bubble-pass (cons b rest)))))))))\n\n(define (bubble-sort lst passes-left)\n  (cond\n    ((<= passes-left 0) lst)\n    (else (bubble-sort (bubble-pass lst) (- passes-left 1)))))\n\n(display (bubble-sort '(3 1 4 1 5 9 2 6) 8)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\ncompare: 3 vs 1\nswap: 3 vs 1\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 1\nswap: 4 vs 1\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 9\ncompare: 9 vs 2\nswap: 9 vs 2\ncompare: 9 vs 6\nswap: 9 vs 6\ncompare: 1 vs 3\ncompare: 3 vs 1\nswap: 3 vs 1\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 2\nswap: 4 vs 2\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 6 vs 9\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 1 vs 3\ncompare: 3 vs 2\nswap: 3 vs 2\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 6 vs 9\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 1 vs 2\ncompare: 2 vs 3\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 6 vs 9\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 1 vs 2\ncompare: 2 vs 3\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 6 vs 9\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 1 vs 2\ncompare: 2 vs 3\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 6 vs 9\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 1 vs 2\ncompare: 2 vs 3\ncompare: 3 vs 4\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 6 vs 9\n(1 1 2 3 4 5 6 9)\n```\n\nFifty-six compares and eight swaps for an eight-element list. That is the \"as slow as it looks\" part.\n\n## Insertion sort\n\nInsertion sort keeps a sorted prefix on the left and inserts the next element into its right place. Fewer compares than bubble on almost-sorted data.\n\n```scheme\n(define (trace label a b)\n  (display label) (display \": \")\n  (display a) (display \" vs \") (display b) (newline))\n\n(define (insert x sorted)\n  (cond\n    ((null? sorted) (list x))\n    (else\n     (trace 'compare x (car sorted))\n     (cond\n       ((<= x (car sorted)) (cons x sorted))\n       (else (cons (car sorted) (insert x (cdr sorted))))))))\n\n(define (insertion-sort lst)\n  (let loop ((rest lst) (sorted '()))\n    (cond\n      ((null? rest) sorted)\n      (else (loop (cdr rest) (insert (car rest) sorted))))))\n\n(display (insertion-sort '(3 1 4 1 5 9 2 6))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\ncompare: 1 vs 3\ncompare: 4 vs 1\ncompare: 4 vs 3\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 5 vs 1\ncompare: 5 vs 1\ncompare: 5 vs 3\ncompare: 5 vs 4\ncompare: 9 vs 1\ncompare: 9 vs 1\ncompare: 9 vs 3\ncompare: 9 vs 4\ncompare: 9 vs 5\ncompare: 2 vs 1\ncompare: 2 vs 1\ncompare: 2 vs 3\ncompare: 6 vs 1\ncompare: 6 vs 1\ncompare: 6 vs 2\ncompare: 6 vs 3\ncompare: 6 vs 4\ncompare: 6 vs 5\ncompare: 6 vs 9\n(1 1 2 3 4 5 6 9)\n```\n\nTwenty-three compares — less than half of bubble's fifty-six on the same input. That is the \"as tidy as it looks\" part.\n\n## Quicksort\n\nQuicksort picks a pivot, partitions the rest into \"less than pivot\" and \"not less than pivot,\" recurses on both. In Scheme this fits in about ten lines.\n\n```scheme\n(define (trace label a b)\n  (display label) (display \": \")\n  (display a) (display \" vs \") (display b) (newline))\n\n(define (partition-less pivot lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        (else (trace 'compare (car lst) pivot)\n              (cond ((< (car lst) pivot)\n                     (cons (car lst) (partition-less pivot (cdr lst))))\n                    (else (partition-less pivot (cdr lst)))))))\n\n(define (partition-ge pivot lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        (else (cond ((< (car lst) pivot) (partition-ge pivot (cdr lst)))\n                    (else (cons (car lst) (partition-ge pivot (cdr lst))))))))\n\n(define (quicksort lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        ((null? (cdr lst)) lst)\n        (else\n         (let ((p (car lst)) (rest (cdr lst)))\n           (append\n             (quicksort (partition-less p rest))\n             (cons p (quicksort (partition-ge p rest))))))))\n\n(display (quicksort '(3 1 4 1 5 9 2 6))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\ncompare: 1 vs 3\ncompare: 4 vs 3\ncompare: 1 vs 3\ncompare: 5 vs 3\ncompare: 9 vs 3\ncompare: 2 vs 3\ncompare: 6 vs 3\ncompare: 1 vs 1\ncompare: 4 vs 6\ncompare: 5 vs 6\ncompare: 9 vs 6\ncompare: 4 vs 5\ncompare: 9 vs 9\n(1 1 2 3 4 5 6 9)\n```\n\nThirteen compares on the same input. Different again, and different in a way you can see in the trace: each pivot's compares cluster, then the recursion breaks into smaller clusters.\n\n## Dot-matrix rendering\n\nThe trace layer is fine, but for the visualization payoff you want to see the *state of the list* after each swap, drawn as bars. A tiny renderer that maps numbers to `#` characters.\n\n```scheme\n(define (bar n)\n  (let loop ((k 0) (acc \"\"))\n    (if (>= k n) acc (loop (+ k 1) (string-append acc \"#\")))))\n\n(define (render-list lst)\n  (let loop ((xs lst))\n    (cond ((null? xs) 'done)\n          (else (display (bar (car xs))) (newline) (loop (cdr xs))))))\n\n(render-list '(3 1 4 1 5 9 2 6))\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n###\n#\n####\n#\n#####\n#########\n##\n######\ndone\n```\n\nA crude dot-matrix histogram. In a real UI, this would be pixel bars; in the REPL, `#`-strings work fine. The visualization is the same idea either way.\n\n## Sort-and-render\n\nBringing it together — the render printed after each pass of bubble sort, so you see the list shape settle.\n\n```scheme\n(define (bar n)\n  (let loop ((k 0) (acc \"\"))\n    (if (>= k n) acc (loop (+ k 1) (string-append acc \"#\")))))\n(define (render-list lst)\n  (let loop ((xs lst))\n    (cond ((null? xs) 'done)\n          (else (display (bar (car xs))) (newline) (loop (cdr xs))))))\n\n(define (bubble-pass lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        ((null? (cdr lst)) lst)\n        (else (let ((a (car lst)) (b (cadr lst)) (rest (cddr lst)))\n                (cond ((> a b) (cons b (bubble-pass (cons a rest))))\n                      (else    (cons a (bubble-pass (cons b rest)))))))))\n\n(define (bubble-sort-visual lst passes)\n  (cond ((<= passes 0) lst)\n        (else\n         (display \"--- pass ---\") (newline)\n         (render-list lst)\n         (bubble-sort-visual (bubble-pass lst) (- passes 1)))))\n\n(bubble-sort-visual '(3 1 4 5 2) 5)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n--- pass ---\n###\n#\n####\n#####\n##\n--- pass ---\n#\n###\n####\n##\n#####\n--- pass ---\n#\n###\n##\n####\n#####\n--- pass ---\n#\n##\n###\n####\n#####\n--- pass ---\n#\n##\n###\n####\n#####\n(1 2 3 4 5)\n```\n\nFive passes, and you can watch the taller bars migrate down. The last two passes are unchanged — the sort has settled.\n\n## Comparing sort behaviors\n\nOne small program that runs all three sorts on the same input and reports compare counts, so the \"why quicksort is fast\" claim becomes a measurement.\n\n```scheme\n(define compares 0)\n(define (bump) (set! compares (+ compares 1)))\n\n(define (bubble-pass lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '()) ((null? (cdr lst)) lst)\n        (else (let ((a (car lst)) (b (cadr lst)) (rest (cddr lst)))\n                (bump)\n                (cond ((> a b) (cons b (bubble-pass (cons a rest))))\n                      (else    (cons a (bubble-pass (cons b rest)))))))))\n(define (bubble-sort lst passes)\n  (cond ((<= passes 0) lst) (else (bubble-sort (bubble-pass lst) (- passes 1)))))\n\n(define (insert x sorted)\n  (cond ((null? sorted) (list x))\n        (else (bump)\n              (cond ((<= x (car sorted)) (cons x sorted))\n                    (else (cons (car sorted) (insert x (cdr sorted))))))))\n(define (insertion-sort lst)\n  (let loop ((rest lst) (sorted '()))\n    (cond ((null? rest) sorted) (else (loop (cdr rest) (insert (car rest) sorted))))))\n\n(define (partition-less p lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        (else (bump)\n              (cond ((< (car lst) p) (cons (car lst) (partition-less p (cdr lst))))\n                    (else (partition-less p (cdr lst)))))))\n(define (partition-ge p lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        (else (cond ((< (car lst) p) (partition-ge p (cdr lst)))\n                    (else (cons (car lst) (partition-ge p (cdr lst))))))))\n(define (quicksort lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '()) ((null? (cdr lst)) lst)\n        (else (let ((p (car lst)) (rest (cdr lst)))\n                (append (quicksort (partition-less p rest))\n                        (cons p (quicksort (partition-ge p rest))))))))\n\n(define input '(3 1 4 1 5 9 2 6))\n\n(set! compares 0) (bubble-sort input 8)  (display 'bubble) (display \": \") (display compares) (newline)\n(set! compares 0) (insertion-sort input) (display 'insertion) (display \": \") (display compares) (newline)\n(set! compares 0) (quicksort input)      (display 'quicksort) (display \": \") (display compares) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nbubble: 56\ninsertion: 23\nquicksort: 13\n```\n\nFifty-six, twenty-three, thirteen. On this input, quicksort does about a quarter as many compares as bubble. On longer inputs the gap widens further.\n\n## Under the hood — why the trace layer is worth it\n\n> **Under the hood**\n>\n> Compare-and-swap tracing was, historically, how CS courses taught sort behavior on paper. It works because the reader's eye can build a mental model of what the algorithm is doing from the sequence of operations. In modern Scheme code, the trace is a five-line helper that you can leave in place or `set!` a mute variable to silence — same shape as tracing anywhere else. Building a debugger habit into the language early is one of Scheme's quiet wins.\n\n## What you know now\n\n- Sort algorithms come alive when you can see the compares and swaps.\n- Bubble is slow (fifty-six compares on eight elements). Insertion is tidier. Quicksort is the fast one on random data.\n- The trace layer is a tiny helper that shares the same shape across all three sorts.\n- Dot-matrix rendering with `#`-strings is enough for a real visualization in the REPL.\n- Counting compares (with a bumped counter) makes \"quicksort is fast\" a measurement, not a claim.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\nAuthor a sort that is deliberately worse than bubble — a selection sort with the trace layer — and compare its compare count to bubble's.\n\n```scheme\n(define compares 0)\n(define (bump) (set! compares (+ compares 1)))\n\n(define (min-of lst)\n  (let loop ((xs (cdr lst)) (m (car lst)))\n    (cond ((null? xs) m)\n          (else (bump)\n                (if (< (car xs) m) (loop (cdr xs) (car xs)) (loop (cdr xs) m))))))\n\n(define (remove-first x lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        ((equal? (car lst) x) (cdr lst))\n        (else (cons (car lst) (remove-first x (cdr lst))))))\n\n(define (selection-sort lst)\n  (cond ((null? lst) '())\n        (else (let ((m (min-of lst)))\n                (cons m (selection-sort (remove-first m lst)))))))\n\n(set! compares 0)\n(display (selection-sort '(3 1 4 1 5 9 2 6))) (newline)\n(display 'selection) (display \": \") (display compares) (newline)\n```\n\nIf your selection sort's compare count is worse than bubble's, you've reproduced the classic result. On to Chapter 3.\n\n---\n\n*Chapter 3 — Tail recursion.*\n")
